==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flageolet
<hw>Flag"eo*let`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>flageolet</ets>, dim. of OF. <ets>flaj<?/l</ets> (as if fr. a LL.
<ets>flautio</ets>;<ets>us</ets>), of <ets>fla⟦uum⟧te</ets>,
<ets>flahute</ets>, F. <ets>fl<?/te</ets>. See <er>Flute</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A small wooden pipe, having six or more holes,
and a mouthpiece inserted at one end. It produces a shrill sound, softer
than of the piccolo flute, and is said to have superseded the old
recorder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flageolet tones</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>the
naturel harmonics or overtones of stringed instruments.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flagginess</ent>⟦br⟧
